These equations are the only ones that are implemented into TRISTAN. Generally, the plasma should also obey the Poisson’s equation. However, instead of solving Poisson’s equation which is solved numerically in almost all particle simulation codes, TRISTAN solves only two curls, i.e., Ampere’s and Faraday’s equations (1) and (2). A rigorous charge conservation method for the current J\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {J}$$\end{document} is described in more detail in Villasenor and Buneman (1992); Umeda et al. (2003). Particles that are initialized as unmagnetized Maxwell distribution are updated by the leap-frog method using the magnetic and electric fields as an input. In order to get the correct field values, linear interpolation is employed throughout the code. In the TRISTAN-MPI (Niemiec et al. 2008; Toggweiler et al. 2014; Winkel et al. 2015) higher-order interpolation schemes are employed for solving the Maxwell and Newton-Lorentz equations.

