Melzani et al. (2013) present the parallel PIC code Apar-T and, more importantly, address the fundamental question of the relation amongst PIC models, the Vlasov–Maxwell theory, and real plasmas. They presented four validation tests: spectra from simulations of thermal plasmas, linear growth rates of the relativistic tearing and the filamentation instabilities, and nonlinear filamentation merging phase. Plasmas in nature contain millions to tens of billions of particles per Debye sphere, and relevant microphysical phenomena spread over numerous Debye lengths. It is impossible to track these particles one by one. Rather, the numerical particles represent numerous real particles, and are consequently called superparticles. A superparticle represents either p real ions (having then a rest mass msp=p×mi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
